        <svcproc svcproctype="replace" graphiccount="2">
            <title>SERVICE PROCEDURE</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove original drop tie rod assembly and tie rod arms (lower steering arms) from
                    knuckles (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9102011">Figure 1</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f9102011" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9102011.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 1. Remove Original Tie Rod Assembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After removing both tie rod arms (lower steering arms) from knuckles, re-install the
                    left tie rod arm on right knuckle and the right tie rod arm on the left knuckle (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9102012">Figure 2</hotlnk>). Tighten the tie rod arm nut to 300 to 400 ft. lbs.
                    (407 to 544 Nm). If cotter key cannot be installed, rotate nut to next position and install cotter
                    pin.
                    <emph type="bold">DO NOT BACK OFF NUT TO INSTALL COTTER PIN.</emph>
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f9102012" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9102012.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 2. Reversing Tie Rod Arms (Lower Steering Arms) And Installing New Tie Rod Assembly
                </caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. RIGHT TIE ROD ARM (LOWER STEERING ARM) INSTALLED ON LEFT KNUCKLE</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. LEFT TIE ROD ARM (LOWER STEERING ARM) INSTALLED ON RIGHT KNUCKLE</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. NEW TIE ROD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Assemble the new tie rod ends and tube to the same length as the original set removed
                    from the vehicle. Tighten the tie rod clamp bolts until
                    <emph type="bold">snug, prior to setting toe-in</emph>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the new tie rod assembly from the bottom side of the tie rod arm with the nut,
                    resting against the top of the tie rod arm boss instead of the bottom (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9102012">Figure 2</hotlnk>). Tighten nuts to 120 to 160 ft. lbs. (163 to 280 Nm).
                    If cotter key cannot be installed, rotate nut to next position and install cotter pin.
                    <emph type="bold">DO NOT BACK OFF NUT TO INSTALL COTTER PIN</emph>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>When installing the tie rod assembly, position the clamp so the head of the clamp bolt is
                        facing the axle.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Reset toe-in to the following:</para>
                <para>1/16 inch &#177; 1/32 inch</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Tighten the tie rod clamp nut to 45 - 60 ft. lb. (61 to 88 Nm).</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Turn wheels to maximum left and right position to check for interference between the tie
                    rod clamp and axle and that there is at least 3/4 inch tire clearance. Axle stops may require slight
                    adjustment.
                    <emph type="bold">STEERING GEAR MUST RELIEVE PRIOR TO STOP BOLT CONTACT.</emph>
                </para>
            </step1>
